</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H7307">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">ר֥וּחַ</span>
  <span class="word-translit">Ruach</span>
  <span class="word-english">spirit</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h7307.html">H7307</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H3467">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">יוֹשִֽׁיעַ\׃</span>
  <span class="word-translit">yoShia&#x27;</span>
  <span class="word-english">he delivers</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h3467.html">H3467</a></span>
</span></div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> The psalmist is using the expression **Yahweh is close** as a common expression of the culture to mean that he is ready to help. If this expression does not have that meaning in your language, you could use a comparable expression or state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [Yahweh is always ready to give help]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> The psalmist is using the adjective **brokenhearted** as a noun to mean a brokenhearted person. Deep sadness is spoken of as if the person’s heart is broken. (See also: [[ Alternate translation: [to people who are very sad]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> Here the psalmist is speaking of people who are deeply discouraged as **those who are crushed in spirit**. Your language may have a comparable expression that you could use in your translation, or you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [people who are deeply discouraged]
    </div><div class="interlinear-verse hebrew-verse"><span class="verse-num">19</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H7227">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">רַ֭בּוֹת</span>
