  <span class="word-original hebrew">וְ/שֹׂנְאֵ֖י</span>
  <span class="word-translit">ve/sone&#x27;Ei</span>
  <span class="word-english">and/ those who hate</span>
  <span class="word-strongs">H9002</span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H6662">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">צַדִּ֣יק</span>
  <span class="word-translit">tzaDik</span>
  <span class="word-english">of the righteous</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h6662.html">H6662</a></span>
</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H816">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">יֶאְשָֽׁמוּ\׃</span>
  <span class="word-translit">ye&#x27;Shamu</span>
  <span class="word-english">they will be held guilty</span>
  <span class="word-strongs"><a href="../lexicon/h816.html">H816</a></span>
</span></div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> The psalmist is speaking of **Evil** as if it were a living thing that could kill people. If it would be helpful in your language, you could state the meaning plainly. Alternate translation: [The evil deeds of wicked people will kill them]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> The psalmist uses the adjective **wicked** to refer to wicked people. Your language may use adjectives in the same way. If not, you could translate this with an equivalent phrase. Alternate translation: [the wicked people]
    </div>
    <div class="tn-note">
      <strong>&#x1f4dd; Cultural Note:</strong> The expression **will be condemned** is a passive verbal form. If your language does not use the passive form in this way, you can state this in active form or in another way that is natural in your language. Alternate translation: [Yahweh will condemn those who hate the righteous]
    </div><div class="interlinear-verse hebrew-verse"><span class="verse-num">22</span><span class="interlinear-word" data-strongs="H6299">
  <span class="word-original hebrew">פּוֹדֶ֣ה</span>
